&gt; What do the other pattern glass dealers know about checking pattern
&gt;glass with a black light?

"/> The black (UV) light is not infallible. Basically, it works by causing
fluoresence of trace elements added to the glass to either increase
clarity or to modify the glass color (both slightly or obviously). The
common fluorescing element found in most PG from the last century is
Manganese -- this is the same trace mineral that causes purpling if the
glass is &quot;sun purpled&quot;. (Solar ultraviolet gives the glass a purple
&quot;tan.&quot; I suspect that prolonged exposure to the UV lamp would cause the
same thing but faster. I, at least, regard purpled glass as &quot;damaged&quot;
and so do many other collectors.) Getting back to the point, not all
glass manufacturers of the last century added manganese minerals to their
batch, and some present day manufacturers do add it. Other trace
elements may be more reliable, but you'd have to check with an expert.
(Uranium, for example, was used to color &quot;vaseline&quot; glass -- but it isn't
well-regarded in this nuclear age to include this in tableware, although
the radioactive (and fluorescing) element is probably well-sealed in the
glass and is unlikely to leach out.)
